The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Follow-on issue from Union Bank

 Mumbai, Dec. 29 (PTI): State-owned Union Bank of India today said it will come out with a follow-up offer of 4.5 crore equity shares to raise a projected capital of about Rs 500 crore.

 The issue is part of the banks overall plan to raise Rs 1,200 crore in the next couple of years to meet Basel II norms.

 We have received approvals from both exchanges, BSE and NSE. We wish to come up with the issue before the budget, subject to Sebi approval, UBI chairman and managing director Cherian Varghese said.

 Post-issue, the governments stake in the bank would come down to 55.43 per cent from the current 60.85 per cent, he said and added that the capital adequacy would be over 12 per cent. Varghese said the bank could raise tier-II capital to the tune of Rs 700 crore in the next two years.

 The bank has projected growth of 16.5 per cent in deposits and 21 per cent in credit. As on September 2005, deposits grew more than 23 per cent and credit more than 33 per cent year-on-year, Varghese said. 




